# Many Backers Of Biden in ‘20 Want a Plan B

Voters in Swing States Express Frustration

This article is by Jack Healy, Mitch Senik, Eduardo Medina and David Greene.

PHOENIX — Jeanne Winckus, a 22-year-old at Phoenix, is such a ride-or-deal on President Biden that, on Valentine’s Day, she mailed him a card to say his vigor, passion, would shape the presidential election. But after a week of postcards, she didn’t get the same debate performance, the left coast Democrats send him another card.

This one said: Thanks for everything, but it’s time to go.

“I just love Biden, but he’s real,” she wrote in a card. “Pass the bottle.”

As Mr. Biden and his allies here scratched to fix the damage from the debate last week, and to insist he will have control of the race, dozens of Democratic voters have said they no longer believe he can accomplish the one thing they urgently want — a debate of former president Donald Trump. They are desperate for the party to find a place for it.
